			
			â­ï¸ â­ï¸ â­ï¸ shallow_copy v/s deep_copy : â­ï¸ â­ï¸ â­ï¸

ğŸ‘‰ï¸ in shallow copy all the primitives' "values" are copied
   BUT the objects' "reference" are copied.

	â–¶ï¸ step : 1
		 So, suppose we have an object:
		const obj = {
			a: "aaa",
			b: true,
			c: {
				d: "one",
			},
		};  
		
	 â–¶ï¸ step : 2 
	 	and we "shallow" copy it:
		const clonedObj = {
			...obj,
		};  // here we have used spread operator;
			// same effect can be achieved from Object.assign(target, source)
			
	 â–¶ï¸ step : 3 
	 	if we mutate our original object:
		obj.b = false;
		obj.c.d = "two";
		
	 â–¶ï¸ step : 4
	 	if we check our cloned object:
		console.log(clonedObj)
		// LOGS: {
			a: "aaa",
			b: true,
			c: {
				d: "two",
			},
		};
		//ğŸ‘ï¸â€ğŸ—¨ï¸ï¸ see how primitives remains the same but the object gets modified.
			since we copied the reference of the nested object, any change in the original nested object
			will bring change in the cloned object's nested object.
			
	â˜€ï¸ if we had deep copied it : [Use: clonedeep from lodash, structuredClone() ]
	LOG: {
			a: "aaa",
			b: true,
			c: {
				d: "one",
			},
		};
		//ğŸ‘ï¸â€ğŸ—¨ï¸ï¸ change in original object will not bring change in the cloned object.
	
	
